oc:kn_1cd8e2cf a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SuccessIndicator ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When measuring signup flow performance" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Key metrics to track: form start rate (landed → started), form completion rate (started → submitted), field-level drop-off, time to complete, error rate by field, mobile vs. desktop completion." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Granular metrics enable precise diagnosis of where the signup funnel leaks, informing targeted optimizations." .

oc:kn_1dbc56de a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing or auditing any signup form" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never require more fields than absolutely necessary at signup — every additional field reduces conversion. Defer company, role, team size, phone, and address to progressive profiling." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Field count is the single strongest predictor of signup completion; each field adds friction that compounds drop-off." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_51a7b3ed a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always, at the start of any signup flow CRO engagement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for product-marketing-context.md before asking questions. Read it to understand the product context, then only ask for information not already covered." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Avoids redundant questions and ensures recommendations are grounded in existing product knowledge." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_54d2c4c7 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing multi-step signup flows with 4+ required fields" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For multi-step signup, lead with easy fields (email, name) and place harder questions after psychological commitment. Show a progress indicator. Allow back navigation and save progress on refresh." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Progressive commitment leverages the sunk-cost fallacy: users who've completed easy steps are less likely to abandon at harder ones." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9341b822 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing post-submit verification flows" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Requiring email verification before product access creates a significant drop-off point. Delay verification until necessary or let users explore while awaiting verification." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Users lose momentum when blocked before experiencing value; delayed or parallel verification preserves activation rates." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_c4949cfb a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When architecting the signup flow entry point" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Show value before asking for commitment — let users experience the product before requiring account creation. Reverse the order: value first, signup second." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Users who have already experienced value are significantly more motivated to complete signup, reducing abandonment." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e504778e a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing password and form field UX" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never disable password paste. Never use placeholder-only labels (they disappear when typing). Always show password requirements upfront, not after submission failure." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These anti-patterns create unnecessary friction, confuse users, and increase form abandonment." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_fcd91cd3 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RequiresHumanClarification ;
    oc:appliesToContext "At the start of any signup flow audit or optimization task" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before providing recommendations, clarify: flow type (trial/freemium/paid/waitlist), current state (steps, fields, completion rate, drop-off points), and business constraints (required data, compliance needs, post-signup experience)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Recommendations are only useful when grounded in the specific product context and business requirements." .

